Table 3
 presents the descriptive statistics of the variables. The statistical information is presented in the following order: mean, 1st, 90th, and standard deviation. The mean of Total factors energy efficiency is 3906.501, suggesting more than 3000 units of energy efficiency were used among the sampled countries. However, the standard deviation is higher, indicating high variation among the sampled countries; specifically, Hong Kong has the highest energy efficiency (see Fig. 2
). This may be due to their stringent policy on cleaner energy consumption. Among the sustainable economic development variables (modified/adjusted net saving, GDP of countries per capita, industry-specific value-added, urbanization, and renewable energy consumption), we observed a similar trend except for urbanization with the mean value of 53.746 and a very small standard deviation, suggesting small variation among the sampled countries. Furthermore, most of the variables of sustainable financial development (i.e., domestic or institutional credit facilities for the private sector, financial market, financial institution, and health expenditure) show a low standard deviation value, indicating small variation among the sample countries. In contrast, research and development and foreign direct investment show high standard deviation, suggesting high variation among sampled countries.
